course_title: SELECTED TOPICS IN MGMT: Aboriginal Economic Development: Contemporary Issues in Business and Law
subject: COM

sections.description: This seminar course will examine current business, law, and policy issues that are affecting Aboriginal communities in an effort to analyze and discuss the wide-ranging variables that contribute to successful Aboriginal economic development.  Students will become familiar with the governing frameworks that inform and define Aboriginal, federal, and provincial relations. As well, a review of available business models and case studies will be considered. This will include co-management agreements and other joint ventures.

course_title: SELECTED TOPICS IN MGMT: Climate Capitalism
subject: COM

sections.description: This course draws on case studies of international corporations, small businesses, NGOs, and municipalities to prove that efficiency and renewable energy are the path to greater profitability and enhanced economic prosperity.  The course addresses business opportunities across a range of sectors, including energy, buildings, transportation, and agriculture technologies as well as expose opportunities in carbon markets and adaptation.  The course also takes a philosophical approach to the future of capitalism in a carbon-constrained world and demonstrates that climate change policy will promote, not hinder, growth of our global economy.  The course prepares business students to enter into the business world armed with tools and analysis which will enable them to help their employers or their own businesses to profit from the transition to a low-carbon economy.

course_title: CONTEMPORARY ISSUES:LAW: Aboriginal Economic Development: Contemporary Issues in Business and Law
subject: LAW

sections.description: This seminar course will examine current business, law, and policy issues that are affecting Aboriginal communities in an effort to analyze and discuss the wide-ranging variables that contribute to successful Aboriginal economic development.  Students will become familiar with the governing frameworks that inform and define Aboriginal, federal, and provincial relations. As well, a review of available business models and case studies will be considered. This will include co-management agreements and other joint ventures.
